Journal-d and journal-control, the systemd log system.

Systemd ships with its own logging daemon, systemd journal-d, which collects log messages from absolutely everything, the kernel, every service, and every user session, into a single binary, structured journal. The tool you use to read that journal is journal-control.

The advantages over the old approach of tailing a pile of text files in slash var slash log are real. Everything lands in one unified place, tagged with rich metadata: which service produced it, which user, which process, and what severity. That metadata makes filtering powerful, so instead of grepping across eight different files you ask precise questions. And the journal can be either volatile, lost at reboot, which is the default, or made persistent with a small change.

The basic commands are straightforward. Journal-control on its own shows the whole journal; with dash e it jumps to the end, with dash f it follows live like tail, with dash n and a number it shows the last so-many entries, and with dash r it reverses to newest-first. The real value, though, is in filtering. Dash u, naming a service, shows only that service's entries, and you can combine it with follow to watch one service live. The since and until options restrict to a time range, accepting friendly phrases like one hour ago or today. Dash p filters by priority, so you can ask for only errors and worse. Dash b restricts to a particular boot: the current boot, or the previous one, which is exactly how you investigate why the last boot failed. And dash k shows only kernel messages, largely replacing the old d-mesg command. Between filtering by unit, by time, by priority, and by boot, journal-control turns log hunting from a chore into a precise query.
